### Describe the bug

Http1OutputProducer does not handle GetSpan/GetMemory(sizeHint: 0) correctly.

Taking a look at:
https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/d26729ef12e126cb15ce65d15bdef7fcf31c4e60/src/Servers/Kestrel/Core/src/Internal/Http/Http1OutputProducer.cs#L756

we can see the code is passing sizeHint - which travels untouched all the way from HttpResponse.BodyWriter - directly into the memory pool GetMemory method.

The issue arises as the semantics between these APIs are subtly different. When it comes to `0` size hints MemoryPool has the freedom to return an empty buffer while PipeWriter/IBufferWriter must produce a non-empty buffer. 

The default PinnedBlockMemoryPool does not run into this due to its particular implementation, however something more standard like MemoryPool.Shared will.

This was discovered while testing a custom transport using MemoryPool.Shared.

### Expected Behavior

A fix should be made to avoid passing 0 to the IMemoryPool.GetMemory calls in Http1OutputProducer AddSegment and GetFakeMemory (there may also be more affected Rent calls lurking in other classes, I've only investigated this particular case)

With the correctness issue fixed, things are not immediately ideal though. As memory pools hold very tiny to very large buckets passing something like sizeHint 1 or 10 would give you a 16 byte buffer back, unlikely to be sufficient for even the smallest bodies. That then usually causes significant performance issues due to advancing and requesting more memory (all the way to the pool) far too frequently.

I see two simple ways to improve this aspect:
- Expect the transport to handle this (documenting IMemoryPoolFeature.MemoryPool should always return reasonably sized buffers) 
- Supply some reasonable default in Http1OutputProducer (and other IMemoryPoolFeature dependents) when working with size hint 0.

### Steps To Reproduce

I can't point to the custom transport but Sockets has an internal config knob to show the problem:

```cs
using System.Buffers;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.Sockets;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateSlimBuilder(args);

builder.WebHost.UseSockets(options =>
{
    PoolAccessor.SetMemoryPoolFactory(options, () => MemoryPool<byte>.Shared);
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapGet("/test", context => context.Response.BodyWriter.GetMemory(sizeHint: 0).Length is 0 ? throw new Exception("Length is 0") : Task.CompletedTask);

await app.RunAsync();

static class PoolAccessor
{
    [UnsafeAccessor(UnsafeAccessorKind.Method, Name = "set_MemoryPoolFactory")]
    public static extern void SetMemoryPoolFactory(SocketTransportOptions options, Func<MemoryPool<byte>> factory);
}
```

Run the sample, navigate to `http://localhost:5000/test`, see the logs print the exception.


